> That&#x27;s a huge assumption<p>I am not talking about optimizations that require understandings of the source language. But, for a simple example, a Pascal-ish language may have the statement<p><pre><code>  x := (a+b)*(c+d)
</code></pre>
compile into something like:<p><pre><code>  _t1 = a + b;
  _t2 = c + d;
  _t3 = _t1 * _t2;
  x = _t3;
</code></pre>
in order to simplify translation from an internal representation such as an AST. Putting such a piece of code back into human readable form makes the backend more complicated, while C compiler know how to optimize away the extraneous variables well.<p>Note that this is just one of many things that contribute to the verbosity of compiler output, not even necessarily a major one in this case.
